# Accessibility (WCAG 2.2 AA)

Accessibility is a hard requirement, not a nice-to-have. All UI must meet **WCAG 2.2 level
AA**. Prioritise colour contrast and full keyboard operability.

## Colour & contrast

- Text contrast >= **4.5:1** (>= **3:1** for large text >= 24px / 18.66px bold).
- Non-text UI (icons, borders, form controls, focus indicators, states) >= **3:1**.
- Never convey meaning by colour alone — pair with text, icon or pattern.
- Verify token pairings (see `docs/design-system.md`) in both light and dark mode.

## Keyboard

- Everything operable with a pointer must be operable by keyboard, in a logical tab order.
- All interactive elements are focusable and have a **visible focus indicator** (use the
  `ring`/`ring-offset` utilities; never `outline: none` without a replacement).
- No keyboard traps; manage focus for dialogs/menus/drawers (focus in on open, return on
  close). Support `Esc` to close and arrow keys where expected (prefer Radix primitives,
  which handle this).

## Semantics & content

- Use native elements first (`button`, `a`, `label`, `nav`, `main`, headings in order).
  Reach for ARIA only when no native element fits — and test it.
- Every image needs meaningful `alt` (empty `alt=""` for decorative). Icon-only buttons need
  an accessible name (`aria-label`).
- Associate form inputs with `<label>`; surface errors in text, linked via `aria-describedby`.
- Respect `prefers-reduced-motion`; don't rely on hover-only interactions.

## Definition of Done

Keyboard-only pass, visible focus everywhere, contrast checked (both themes), and semantic
markup. Consider an automated check (axe) in the component preview.
